    <h2>Pricing Strategy Takeaways</h2>
    <div class="section-desc">What the data reveals about how Stellantis structures pricing across its portfolio</div>
    <div class="strategy-grid">
      <div class="strategy-card">
        <span class="tag margin">Margin Structure</span>
        <h3>Two-Tier Option Margin System</h3>
        <p>Jeep, Dodge, and Chrysler consistently price options at ~10% over FWP. RAM uses ~8%. RAM compensates with higher base model margins (5.4% vs 2-3%), creating different profit profiles depending on how heavily a vehicle is optioned.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="strategy-card">
        <span class="tag volume">Powertrain</span>
        <h3>Cummins Diesel is the Profit King</h3>
        <p>At $12,995 MSRP with ~$1,039 spread, the Cummins diesel engine generates more margin dollars per unit than most vehicles' entire base markup. It appears on HD trucks that already carry 5.5%+ base margins.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="strategy-card">
        <span class="tag structure">Bundling</span>
        <h3>Opaque Package Bundling</h3>
        <p>Jeep "Customer Preferred Packages" bundle 20-40 sub-items into $5K-$11K packages at 10% margin. Individual sub-items often show $0 MSRP/$0 FWP, making it impossible for consumers to price features individually.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="strategy-card">
        <span class="tag hidden">Hidden Costs</span>
        <h3>Invisible Wholesale Charges</h3>
        <p>"T3AC" (code 4UQ) appears on every RAM at $0 MSRP but $125 FWP — a wholesale charge invisible to consumers. Holdback ($1,300-$3,000) and floor plan ($400-$800) further widen the true MSRP-to-cost gap.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="strategy-card">
        <span class="tag margin">Trim Strategy</span>
        <h3>Trim Levels as Margin Expanders</h3>
        <p>RAM 1500 Tungsten ($88K, 6.8% base markup) vs Tradesman ($48K, 3.8%) shows how higher trims dramatically expand base margins. Jeep Grand Wagoneer stays flat at ~4% regardless of trim.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="strategy-card">
        <span class="tag volume">Volume Mix</span>
        <h3>Wrangler Rubicon is King</h3>
        <p>746 invoices make it the top-volume model, averaging $64K MSRP with a 4.1% invoice discount. RAM 1500 Rebel (452 invoices) and RAM 2500 Tradesman (360) follow. These three models likely drive the bulk of Carvana's Stellantis new car business.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="strategy-card">
        <span class="tag structure">Price Architecture</span>
        <h3>Deeper Waterfalls on Trucks</h3>
        <p>RAM trucks discount 5-6% MSRP-to-invoice vs just 2% for Jeep Grand Cherokee. Employee pricing adds another 4-6%, meaning total MSRP-to-floor ranges from 7% (Jeep) to 11%+ (RAM). Some RAM 2500 trims show 17-22% employee discount anomalies.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="strategy-card">
        <span class="tag hidden">Data Quality</span>
